Session prompts that produced this commit
==========================================

[1] Ok, I want to think through a new Go based app that we will build in this
repo. For this first session, we're not coding anything. What we want as a work
product is a detailed design document that we can use as a blueprint for building
the app. The app will be:
- A combination of an RSS reader and an email client.
- The entire app will be built in Go, and will run as a TUI.
- TUI inspired by charmbracelet and the Bubble Tea framework, but not beholden
  to it; deviate where needed.
The idea: a TUI with a continuous feed of content (RSS items + emails) the user
can interact with — filter by criteria (only emails, only RSS, by source), mark
items read/unread, open items to view full content. Support multiple Gmail
accounts and RSS feeds via OPML files, but not a full client — just pull content
and display it. Marking read/unread can be local-only (color change), no syncing
state back to Gmail/RSS for v1. Produce a detailed design document outlining
architecture, main components, data models, and user interactions.

[2] Ok. Can you write the design document to a 'design' directory in this repo?

[3] Take the design just written and think through the implementation steps.
Output is twofold: (a) a step-by-step design document containing an overview, and
(b) for each step, a document describing the step in detail, including code
samples, validation criteria, and implementation flow. All docs written in the
design directory.

[4] /trueup — commit the work, add prompts in this session to the commit via git
notes, push, and create a PR via the GitHub CLI. Ensure the PR README accurately
describes the changes from a full diff against the base branch.

Decisions confirmed via clarifying questions
--------------------------------------------
- Email access: Gmail API + OAuth2 (read-only scope), per-account browser flow.
- Persistence: SQLite caching both items and read/unread state.
- Layout: full-screen unified list -> drill into a full-screen reader.
- Rendering: rich HTML -> markdown -> Glamour.
- Doc granularity: one doc per build phase (8 step docs + 1 overview).
- Code depth: representative skeletons (not full paste-ready files).
- Location: design/implementation/ (DESIGN.md at design/ top level).
